  "prompt": "What are the best dialogues from the movie Masaan?",
  "response": "\"Masaan,\" directed by Neeraj Ghaywan, is known for its poignant and beautifully crafted dialogues that reflect the complexities of life, love, and loss. Here are some of the most memorable dialogues from the movie:\n\n1. **\"Ye dukh kaahe khatam nahi hota be?\"** - Deepak\n   This line captures the deep sorrow and longing embedded within the character and his circumstances.\n\n2. **\"Saala yeh dukh kahan khatam hota hai!\"** - Deepak\n   It mirrors the unending anguish faced by the characters, resonating deeply with the audience.\n\n3. **\"Lagaav ka koi naam nahin hota, bass ehsaas hota hai.\"** - Devi's father\n   This line, spoken by Devi's father, captures the essence of connection and love beyond societal labels.\n\n4. **\"Tu jab aawe hai, jaise muebile mein network aa jawe hai.\"** - Deepak\n   It highlights the significance of his beloved in Deepak's life, symbolizing connectivity and emotional bonding.\n\n5. **\"Sadak kinare zindagi bazaar mein bichhi hai, aur maut kehti hai\u2026\"** - Shaalu's poetry\n   Shaalu\u2019s character adds profound depth through her poetry.\n\n6. **\"Ganga mein sab beh jaata hai...kya dukh, kya sukh.\"** - Deepak\n   This dialogue reflects the multifaceted nature of life and the cleansing, cathartic impact of the Ganges.\n\n7. **\"Hum abhi aise hi milte hain chori-chori, chhupke-chhupke...jaise chori kar rahe ho hum.\"** - Deepak\n   The clandestine nature of Deepak\u2019s relationship with Shaalu highlights societal pressures and personal dilemmas.\n\nThese dialogues are reflective of the movie's profound narrative and character arcs, making \"Masaan\" a deeply affecting cinematic experience.",
